----------------------------------- Cronjob ------------------------------------------
A cron job is a scheduled task in Linux/Unix systems that runs automatically at specified times or intervals.
It is managed by the cron daemon (background service).
Cronjob = Think of cron as a scheduler:
          Run a backup every day at midnight.
          Execute a script every 5 minutes.
          Send reports every Monday at 8 AM.
          Clean temporary files weekly.

Cron systex = * * * * * command_to_run
              │ │ │ │ │
              │ │ │ │ └── Day of Week (0-7)
              │ │ │ └──── Month (1-12)
              │ │ └────── Day of Month (1-31)
              │ └──────── Hour (0-23)
              └────────── Minute (0-59)
Ex:- 30 2 * * * /home/user/backup.sh
      Minute = 30
      Hour = 2
      Every day
      Every month
      Every weekday
      
      Ans = Runs at 2:30 AM daily.

What is Crontab = Crontab (Cron Table) is a file that stores a user's scheduled cron jobs.

Commands:  crontab -e   # Edit cron jobs
            crontab -l   # List cron jobs
            crontab -r   # Remove cron jobs
User Cronjob stored = /var/spool/cron/ or /var/spool/cron/crontabs/
System Cronjob stored = /etc/crontab
Special cronjob Dirrcytories = /etc/cron.hourly/
                              /etc/cron.daily/
                              /etc/cron.weekly/
                              /etc/cron.monthly/
