---------------------------------- Links -----------------------------------------------------
Links =  link is a pointer or shortcut that connects a filename to the actual data stored on the storage drive.
:- Besically There are Two type of Links,
a) Symbolic link ( Soft ) 
b) Hard Link 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
a) Symbolic link ( Soft ) = A symbolic link is a standalone file that stores the directory path of the target file. When you open a symlink,
                              the system automatically redirects you to the target path. If the target file is renamed or deleted, 
                            the soft link points to nothing and stops functioni
soft link = ln -s [ Source path file ] and [ Destination path file ]  { f = fource fully create a link without its check there is a link present or not }
Advantages:- Lesser in size than the source file.
Dis-advantage:- If source file is deleted there is no use of soft link.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Hard link = A hard link creates a direct correlation between a new file name and the underlying data storage block (inode).
              In Linux, a file is only completely erased when all of its hard links are deleted. By default, every normal file you create 
            has exactly one hard link. If you delete the original file name, you can still access the intact data through any remaining hard links
Hard link = ln [ Source path file name ] [ Destination path file name ]
Advantage:- It work wehen source file is deleted,
Dis-advantage:- Size is same as source file it will consume so much spaces.
